### Naming Convention
`test_<unit>_<scenario>_<expected_behavior>`

```python
def test_user_can_be_created_with_valid_email():
    user = create_user("test@example.com")
    assert user.email == "test@example.com"

def test_user_creation_fails_with_invalid_email():
    with pytest.raises(ValueError):
        create_user("not-an-email")
```

### One Assert Per Test

```python
# ✅ Good: Each test has single purpose
def test_user_email_is_set():
    user = create_user("test@example.com")
    assert user.email == "test@example.com"

def test_user_id_is_generated():
    user = create_user("test@example.com")
    assert user.id is not None

# ❌ Bad: Multiple assertions = unclear failure
def test_user_creation():
    user = create_user("test@example.com")
    assert user.email == "test@example.com"  # Which failed?
    assert user.id is not None
```

### Parametrize for Data-Driven Tests

```python
@pytest.mark.parametrize("input,expected", [
    (1, 2),
    (2, 3),
    (0, 1),
    (-1, 0),
])
def test_increment(input, expected):
    assert increment(input) == expected
```
